<h2 style="margin:0 0 16px;font-size:20px;font-weight:600;color:#111;line-height:1.3;">
  {{ notification.title | e }}
</h2>

<p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-size:15px;line-height:1.6;color:#374151;">
  {{ notification.body | e }}
</p>

{% if notification.meta.percent_used %}
<table role="presentation" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="margin:0 0 20px;background:#f9fafb;border-radius:6px;width:100%;">
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:12px 14px;font-size:13px;color:#6b7280;">
      Disk usage
    </td>
    <td style="padding:12px 14px;font-size:13px;color:#111;font-family:ui-monospace,Menlo,Consolas,monospace;text-align:right;">
      {{ notification.meta.percent_used | e }}%
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
{% endif %}

<p style="margin:0 0 20px;padding:14px;background:#fef3c7;border-left:3px solid #f59e0b;font-size:14px;color:#78350f;line-height:1.5;">
  <strong>This is YOUR hardware</strong> — the host machine running
  CameraNode, not the Command Center's cloud disk.  When it fills, the
  CameraNode will stop writing new local recordings.  Live streaming
  keeps working, but recorded segments stop persisting.
</p>

<p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-size:14px;color:#6b7280;font-weight:600;">
  What to do
</p>
<ul style="margin:0 0 24px;padding-left:20px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.6;color:#374151;">
  <li>Free up space on the host (delete old recordings).</li>
  <li>Lower the recording retention cap in the per-camera recording policy so the node prunes more aggressively.</li>
  <li>Expand the host's storage (mount a larger drive, swap the SD card on a Pi, etc.).</li>
</ul>

<table role="presentation" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
  <tr>
    <td style="background:#22c55e;border-radius:6px;">
      <a href="{{ dashboard_url }}/settings"
         style="display:inline-block;padding:10px 18px;font-size:14px;font-weight:600;color:#0a0a0f;text-decoration:none;">
        Open settings →
      </a>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:24px 0 0;font-size:13px;color:#9ca3af;line-height:1.5;">
  This alert went only to organization admins.  You'll get a
  follow-up email if the disk stays low after 6 hours.
</p>
